00:48:48.100 --> 00:48:51.900
that we don't want to
call them as being say

00:48:51.900 --> 00:48:55.500
class-driven, or
driven by gender anxiety,

00:48:55.500 --> 00:48:57.300
or driven by
political anxiety.

00:48:57.300 --> 00:48:59.967
Oh, it's all going to
be coded in racial ways.

00:48:59.967 --> 00:49:01.667
But because, you know, we
don't want to be seen as

00:49:01.667 --> 00:49:03.100
racist, we can't
talk about it.

00:49:03.100 --> 00:49:05.767
We can show it, but we
can't talk about it.

00:49:05.767 --> 00:49:06.967
So I really
want to end then,

00:49:06.967 --> 00:49:09.600
and just bear with
me a couple minutes,

00:49:09.600 --> 00:49:11.300
we've gone through
this entire course

00:49:11.300 --> 00:49:14.200
thinking--sharing a
history of social,

00:49:14.200 --> 00:49:16.500
political, intellectual,
cultural history,

00:49:16.500 --> 00:49:18.000
of the different ways
citizenship has been

00:49:18.000 --> 00:49:21.100
wrestled over, the
way race has been used.

00:49:21.100 --> 00:49:23.467
The TAs, I hope you will
actually join me in giving,

00:49:23.467 --> 00:49:25.300
giving them a round of
applause for helping us

00:49:25.300 --> 00:49:27.967
through this way and through
these incredibly interesting

00:49:27.967 --> 00:49:29.967
and, and, and
vexed conversations.

00:49:29.967 --> 00:49:30.967
Congratulations.

00:49:30.967 --> 00:49:36.200
Thank you so
much for your help.

00:49:36.200 --> 00:49:39.067
Now I always do something
a little bit unusual here.

00:49:39.067 --> 00:49:40.667
